Of all the primes in the prime factorization of \begin{align*}\gcd(&2^23^35^57^711^{11}13^{13}17^{17}19^{19}23^{23}, \\ &\quad 2^{23}3^{19}5^{17}7^{13}11^{11}13^717^519^323^2),\end{align*}which prime appears with largest exponent?
inference:
The greatest common divisor of two numbers is the product of all the prime factors that they share, raised to the lowest power they appear in either number.

The prime 2 appears with the exponents 2 and 23 in the two numbers, respectively. The smaller exponent is 2.

The prime 3 appears with the exponents 3 and 19, with the smaller exponent being 3.

The prime 5 appears with exponents 5 and 17, with the smaller exponent being 5.

The prime 7 appears with exponents 7 and 13, with the smaller exponent being 7.

The prime 11 appears with exponent 11 in both numbers.

The prime 13 appears with exponents 13 and 7, with the smaller exponent being 7.

The prime 17 appears with exponents 17 and 5, with the smaller exponent being 5.

The prime 19 appears with exponents 19 and 3, with the smaller exponent being 3.

The prime 23 appears with exponents 23 and 2, with the smaller exponent being 2.

The prime appearing with the largest exponent is $\boxed{11}$, because it appears with an exponent of 11 in the GCD.  Final Answer: $\boxed{11}$. I hope it is correct.
ground_truth:
The greatest common divisor of $2^a3^b5^c\cdots$ and $2^{a'}3^{b'}5^{c'}\cdots$ is $$2^{\min\{a,a'\}}3^{\min\{b,b'\}}5^{\min\{c,c'\}}\cdots.$$That is, each prime occurs with the smaller of the two exponents with which it occurs in the prime factorizations of the original two numbers.

In this case, the prime $11$ occurs with exponent $11$ in both of the original numbers, while all other primes occur with an exponent smaller than $11$ in one of the original numbers. Specifically, \begin{align*}
\gcd(&2^23^35^57^711^{11}13^{13}17^{17}19^{19}23^{23},\\ &\quad 2^{23}3^{19}5^{17}7^{13}11^{11}13^717^519^323^2)
\\=\ & 2^23^35^57^711^{11}13^717^519^323^2.
\end{align*}So, the prime with largest exponent in the $\gcd$ is $\boxed{11}$.
